    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-16T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-16T19:00:00-05:00" n="979"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d979">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/216a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-16T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 16, 1912—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your March 5, 2 p.m., and March 6, 10 p.m. In conveying the text of the following
                    proclamation to the Mexican Government you will say: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>As an evidence of the deep and abiding friendship of the American nation
                            for Mexico and the Mexican people, for whose welfare this Government
                            wishes to show its sympathetic concern, and for your excellency’s
                            information, I have the honor to convey to your excellency the following
                            proclamation which has been issued under date of March 14, 1912, by the
                            President of the United States, whose earnest desire is that the
                            blessings of peace and prosperity shall soon return to the Mexican
                            nation.</p>
                        <p>[Here follows the proclamation of March 14, ante.]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
